{"title_page": "2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA Division I-AA season\n| year = 2003\n| image = NCAA logo.svg\n| image_caption = \n| regular_season = August\u2013November\n| playoffs = November 29\u2013December 19\n| nc_date = [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA Football Championship Game|December 19, 2003]]\n| championship = [[Finley Stadium]]<br>[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n| champions = [[2003 Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football team|Delaware]]\n| payton = [[Jamaal Branch]] (RB, Colgate)\n| buchanan = [[Jared Allen]] (DE, Idaho State)\n}}\n\nThe '''2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season''', part of [[college football]] in the United States organized by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] at the [[Division I-AA]] level, began in August 2003, and concluded with the [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA Football Championship Game]] on December 19, 2003, at [[Finley Stadium]] in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]. The [[2003 Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football team|Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens]] won their first I-AA championship, defeating the [[Colgate Raiders football|Colgate Raiders]] by a final score of 40\u22120.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 NCAA Division I Football Championship|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_champs_records/2012/d1/2012FCSfbchamp.pdf|work=NCAA|publisher=NCAA.org|accessdate=December 29, 2013|pages=16}}</ref>\n\n==Conference changes and new programs==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! School !! 2002 Conference !! 2003 Conference\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Canisius Golden Griffins football|Canisius]] || [[Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference|MAAC]]  || ''Dropped Program''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football|Coastal Carolina]] || ''New Program'' || [[Big South Conference|Big South]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[East Tennessee State Buccaneers football|East Tennessee State]] || [[Southern Conference|Southern]]  || ''Dropped Program''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Elon Phoenix football|Elon]] || [[Big South Conference|Big South]]  || [[Southern Conference|Southern]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Fairfield Stags football|Fairfield]] || [[Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference|MAAC]]  || ''Dropped Program''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Jacksonville State Gamecocks football|Jacksonville State]] || [[Southland Conference|Southland]]  || [[Ohio Valley Conference|Ohio Valley]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[St. John's Red Storm football|St. John's (NY)]] || [[Northeast Conference|Northeast]] || ''Dropped Program''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Samford Bulldogs football|Samford]] || [[NCAA Division I FCS independent schools|I-AA Independent]]  || [[Ohio Valley Conference|Ohio Valley]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[Southeastern Louisiana Lions football|Southeastern Louisiana]] || ''Revived Program'' || [[NCAA Division I FCS independent schools|I-AA Independent]] \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| [[VMI Keydets football|VMI]] || [[Southern Conference|Southern]] || [[Big South Conference|Big South]]\n|}\n\n==Conference standings==\n{| cellpadding=\"5\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Atlantic 10 Conference football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Big Sky Conference football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Big South Conference football standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Gateway Football Conference standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Ivy League football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference football standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Northeast Conference football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Ohio Valley Conference football standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Patriot League football standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2003 Pioneer Football Leag