2020}}\n|location = [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n|event    = ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]''\n|notes    =  WWE recognizes the title reign as ending April 5, 2020, when the match on tape delay.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"NXT12182019\">{{cite web|last=Moore|first=John|title=12/18 NXT TV results: Shayna Baszler vs. Rhea Ripley for the NXT Women\u2019s Championship, Adam Cole vs. Finn Balor for the NXT Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/12/18/12-18-nxt-tv-results-shayna-baszler-vs-rhea-ripley-for-the-nxt-womens-championship-adam-cole-vs-finn-balor-for-the-nxt-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n}}{{PWtitlereign\n|number   = 11\n|champion = {{sortname|Charlotte|Flair}}\n|reign    = 2\n|date     = {{dts|2020|3|25}}\n|days     = {{age in days nts|March 25, 2020}}+\n|days2    = {{age in days nts|April 5, 2020}}+\n|location = [[Orlando, Florida]]\n|event    = [[WrestleMania 36]]<br>Part 2\n|notes    = This was the first time an NXT championship was defended at [[WrestleMania]].<br>WWE recognizes the title reign as beginning April 5, 2020, when the match aired on [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]].<br>Charlotte Flair was previously known simply as Charlotte.\n|ref      = <ref name=\"WM36Part2\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell\u2019s live review of Night Two featuring Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre for the WWE Championship, John Cena vs. \u201cThe Fiend\u201d Bray Wyatt in a Firefly Funhouse match, Edge vs. Randy Orton in a Last Man Standing match, Rhea Ripley vs. Charlotte Flair for the NXT Women\u2019s Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/05/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-two-featuring-brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre-for-the-wwe-championship-john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-in-a-firefly-funhouse-match/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{BundleEnd}}\n\n== Combined reigns ==\n[[File:Shayna Baszler NXT Women's Champion.jpg|thumb|150px|Two-time and longest combined reigning NXT Women's Champion [[Shayna Baszler]]]]\nAs of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTDAY}}, {{CURRENTYEAR}}.\n<!-- DO NOT REMOVE THE WWE COLUMN. THIS IS BASED ON CONSENSUS. THESE ARE WWE'S BELTS, SO THEIR DAYS ARE ALSO RECOGNIZED HERE. THEY ARE LISTED SECOND BECAUSE THE ACTUAL DAYS TAKE PRECEDENCE. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #ffe6bd\"|\u2020\n|Indicates the current champion\n|-\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!Rank\n!Wrestler\n!No. of<br>reigns\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Combined days\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Combined days<br>recognized by WWE\n|-\n!1\n|{{sortname|Shayna|Baszler}} || 2 || 549 || 548\n|-\n!2\n|{{sort|Asuka|[[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]]}} || 1 || 510 || 522\n|-\n!3\n|{{sort|Paige|[[Paige (wrestler)|Paige]]}} || 1 || 308 || 273\n|-\n!4\n|style=\"background: #ffe6bd\"| [[Charlotte Flair|Charlotte / Charlotte Flair]] \u2020 || 2 ||  {{age in days nts|July 11, 2019}}+ || {{age in days nts|July 22, 2019}}+\n|-\n!5\n|{{sort|Bayley|[[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]}} || 1 || colspan=2| 223\n|-\n!6\n|{{sortname|Sasha|Banks}} || 1 || 192 || 191\n|-\n!7\n|{{sortname|Ember|Moon}} || 1 || 140 || 139\n|-\n!8\n|{{sortname|Rhea|Ripley}} || 1 || 98 || 109\n|-\n!9\n|{{sortname|Kairi|Sane|Kairi Hojo}} || 1 || colspan=2|71\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Women in WWE]]\n* [[Women's championships in WWE]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n; Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women in WWE}}\n{{NXT Women's Championship}}\n{{NXT Championships}}\n[[Category:WWE NXT championships]]\n[[Category:WWE women's championships]]\n\n== External Link ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/nxt-womens-championship|title=Official NXT Women's Championship title history}}\n", "name_user": "JDC808", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReigns", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NXT_Women%27s_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Otto of Greece", "text_new": "{{redirect|Otho I|the German king|Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor}}\n{{short description|King of Greece}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name            = Otto I\n|image           = File:Prinz Otto von Bayern Koenig von Griechenland 1833.jpg\n|succession      = [[List of kings of Greece|King of Greece]]\n|reign           = 27 May 1832 \u2013 23 October 1862\n|coronation      = \n|regent          = [[Josef Ludwig von Armansperg]] (1832\u20131835)\n|reg-type        = [[List of Greek regents|Regent]]\n|successor       = [[George I of Greece|George I]]\n|birth_date      = {{Birth date|df=yes|1815|6|1}}\n|birth_place     = [[Salzburg]], [[Austrian Empire|Austria]]\n|death_date      = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1867|7|26|1815|6|1}}\n|death_place     = [[Bamberg]], [[Kingdom of Bavaria|Bavaria]]\n|spouse          = [[Amalia of Oldenburg]]\n|issue           =\n|house           = [[House of Wittelsbach|Wittelsbach]]\n|father          = [[Ludwig I, King of Bavaria|Ludwig I of Bavaria]]\n|mother          = [[Therese of Saxe-Hildburghausen]]\n|religion        = [[Roman Catholicism]]   \n|image_size      = \n|reg-type2       = {{nowrap|Prime Ministers}}\n|regent2         = {{List collapsed|title=''See list''|[[Spyridon Trikoupis]]<br>[[Alexandros Mavrokordatos]]<br>[[Ioannis Kolettis]]<br>Josef Ludwig von Armansperg<br>[[Ignaz von Rudhart]]<br>[[Andreas Metaxas]]<br>[[Constantine Kanaris]]<br>[[Kitsos Tzavelas]]<br>[[Georgios Kountouriotis]]<br>[[Athanasios Miaoulis]]<br>[[Gennaios Kolokotronis]]}}\n|place of burial = [[Theatine Church, Munich|Theatinerkirche, Munich]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Royal styles\n|image = [[Image:Flag of Otto of Greece.svg|40px]]\n|royal name = Otto I of Greece\n|dipstyle = [[Majesty|His Majesty]]\n|offstyle = Your Majesty\n}}\n\n'''Otto''' ({{Lang-el|\u038c\u03b8\u03c9\u03bd}}, ''\u00d3thon''; 1 June 1815&nbsp;\u2013 26 July 1867) was a [[Kingdom of Bavaria|Bavarian prince]] who became the first  [[List of kings of Greece|King]] of [[Kingdom of Greece (Wittelsbach)|Greece]] in 1832 under the [[London Conference of 1832|Convention of London]]. He reigned until he was deposed in 1862.\n\nThe second son of King [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]], Otto ascended the newly created throne of Greece while still a minor. His government was initially run by a three-man {{ill|Regency council of Otto of Greece|el|\u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u038c\u03b8\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1|lt=regency council}} made up of Bavarian court officials. Upon reaching his majority, Otto removed the regents when they proved unpopular with the people, and he ruled as an [[absolute monarch]]. Eventually his subjects' demands for a constitution proved overwhelming, and in the face of an armed (but bloodless) insurrection, Otto granted a constitution in 1843.\n\nThroughout his reign Otto was unable to resolve Greece's poverty and prevent economic meddling from outside. Greek politics in this era were based on affiliations with the three [[European balance of power|Great Powers]] that had guaranteed Greece's independence, [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[France]] and [[Russia]], and Otto's ability to maintain the support of the powers was key to his remaining in power. To remain strong, Otto had to play the interests of each of the Great Powers' Greek adherents against the others, while not irritating the Great Powers. When Greece was blockaded by the British [[Royal Navy]] in 1850 and again in 1854, to stop Greece from attacking the [[Ottoman Empire]] during the [[Crimean War]], Otto's standing amongst Greeks suffered. As a result, there was an assassination attempt on [[Queen Amalia]], and finally in 1862 Otto was deposed while in the countryside. He died in exile in Bavaria in 1867.\n\n==Early life and reign==\n[[File:Otto of Hellas.jpg|thumb|200px|A portrait by [[Gottlieb Bodmer]]]]\n{{Further|Ioannis Kapodistrias|Augustinos Kapodistrias}}\nOtto was born as Prince Otto Friedrich Ludwig of Bavaria at [[Palace of Mirabell|Schloss Mirabell]] in [[Salzburg]] (when it briefly belonged to the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salzburger-schlosskonzerte.at/en/Schloss_Mirabell.htm |title=Salzburger Schlosskonzerte website |publisher=Salzburger-schlosskonzerte.at |accessdate=11 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706094138/http://www.salzburger-schlosskonzerte.at/en/Schloss_Mirabell.htm |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> as the second son of Crown Prince [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]] and [[Therese of Saxe-Hildburghausen]]. His father served there as the Bavarian governor-general. Through his ancestor, the Bavarian Duke [[John II, Duke of Bavaria|John II]], Otto was a descendant of the Byzantine [[Byzantine Emperor|imperial dynasties]] of [[Komnenos]] and [[Laskaris]].\n\nWhen he was elected king, the Great Powers extracted a pledge from Otto's father to restrain him from hostile actions against the [[Ottoman Empire]]. They also insisted that his title be \"King of Greece\", rather than \"King of the Hellenes\", because the latter would imply a claim over the millions of Greeks then still under Turkish rule. Not quite 18, the young prince arrived in Greece with 3,500 Bavarian troops (the [[Bavarian Auxiliary Corps]]) and three Bavarian advisors aboard the British [[frigate]] [[HMS Madagascar (1822)|HMS ''Madagascar'']]. Although he did not speak Greek, he immediately endeared himself to his adopted country by adopting the Greek national costume and Hellenizing his name to \"Othon\" (some English sources, such as [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], call him \"Otho\").\n\nOtto's reign is usually divided into three periods:{{By whom|date=August 2019}}\n* The years of {{ill|Regency council of Otto of Greece|el|\u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u038c\u03b8\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1|lt=Regency Council}}: 1832\u20131835\n* The years of [[Absolute Monarchy]]: 1835\u20131843\n* The years of [[Constitutional Monarchy]]: 1843\u20131862\n\nThe Bavarian advisors were arrayed in a Regency Council, headed by Count [[Josef Ludwig von Armansperg]], who, in Bavaria as minister of finance, had recently succeeded in restoring [[Bavaria]]n credit, at the cost of his popularity. Von Armansperg was the President of the Privy Council and the first representative (or Prime Minister) of the new Greek government. The other members of the Regency Council were [[Karl von Abel]] and [[Georg Ludwig von Maurer]], with whom von Armansperg often clashed. After the king reached his majority in 1835, von Armansperg was made Arch-Secretary, but was called Arch-Chancellor by the Greek press.\n\n[[File:Map Greece expansion 1832-1947-en.svg|thumb|left|Map showing the original territory of the [[Kingdom of Greece]], as laid down in the treaty of 1832 (in dark blue)]]\n\nBritain and the [[Rothschilds|Rothschild]] bank, who were underwriting the Greek loans, insisted on financial stringency from Armansperg. The Greeks were soon more heavily taxed than under Ottoman rule;<ref name=\"Petropulos, John A. 1968\">{{cite book |last=Petropulos |first=John A. |title=Politics and Statecraft in the Kingdom of Greece |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1968 }}</ref> as the people saw it, they had exchanged a hated [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule for government by a foreign [[bureaucracy]], the \"Bavarocracy\" (\u0392\u03b1\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1).\n\nIn addition, the regency showed little respect for local customs. As a [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], Otto himself was viewed as a heretic by many pious Greeks; however, his [[heir]]s would have to be [[Greek Orthodox Church|Orthodox]], according to the terms of the 1843 Constitution.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book |last=Clogg |first=Richard |title=A Short History of Modern Greece |url=https://archive.org/details/shorthistoryofmo0000clog |url-access=registration |location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1979 |isbn=0-521-32837-3 }}</ref>{{page needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nKing Otto brought his personal brewmaster with him, Herr Fuchs, a Bavarian who stayed in Greece after Otto's departure and introduced Greece to beer, under the label \"[[Fix (beer)|Fix]]\".<ref>Dean Karayanis, Catherine Karayanis, ''Regional Greek Cooking'', Hippocrene Books, 2008, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NrIapgM4LwQC&pg=PA262&lpg=PA262&dq=king+otto+herr+fuchs+beer+greece&source=bl&ots=QLW5pkFVV4&sig=6UkdtQlrkU5RJmYWEQcCg8f5lgk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu3MivxMTRAhUG7CYKHVSnBekQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=king%20otto%20herr%20fuchs%20beer%20greece&f=false p. 262].</ref>{{Better source|date=August 2019}}\n\nPopular heroes and leaders of the Greek Revolution, such as generals [[Theodoros Kolokotronis]] and [[Yiannis Makriyiannis]], who opposed the Bavarian-dominated regency, were charged with treason, put in jail and sentenced to death. They were later pardoned under popular pressure, while Greek judges who resisted Bavarian pressure and refused to sign the death warrants ([[Anastasios Polyzoidis]] and [[Georgios Tertsetis]], for instance), were saluted as heroes.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOtto's early reign was also notable for his moving the capital of Greece from [[Nafplion]] to [[Athens]]. His first task as king was to make a detailed archaeological and topographic survey of Athens. He assigned [[Gustav Eduard Schaubert]] and [[Stamatios Kleanthis]]<ref>{{cite book |last= Tung |first= Anthony |authorlink= Anthony Tung |title= Preserving the World's Great Cities: The Destruction and Renewal of the Historic Metropolis |url= https://archive.org/details/preservingworlds00anth |url-access= registration |publisher= Three RIvers Press |year= 2001 |location= New York |pages= [https://archive.org/details/preservingworlds00anth/page/256 256\u2013260] |isbn= 0-609-80815-X}}</ref> to complete this task. At that time, Athens had a population of roughly 4,000\u20135,000 people, located mainly in what today covers the district of [[Plaka]] in [[Athens]].\n\n[[File:Peter von Hess - The Entry of King Othon of Greece in Athens - WGA11387.jpg|thumb|220px|\"The Entry of King Otto in Athens\" by [[Peter von Hess]], 1839]]\n[[File:Chalkis 1830s.jpg|thumb|220px|Men of the [[Hellenic Gendarmerie|Royal Gendarmerie Corps]] which was established after the enthronement of Otto in 1833]]\n\nAthens was chosen as the Greek capital for historical and sentimental reasons, not because it was a large city. At the time, it was a town consisting of only 400 houses at the foot of the [[Acropolis]]. A modern city plan was laid out, and public buildings erected. The finest legacy of this period are the buildings of the [[University of Athens]] (1837, under the name Othonian University), the [[National Technical University of Athens|Athens Polytechnic University]] (1837, under the name Royal School of Arts), the [[National Gardens of Athens]] (1840), the [[National Library of Greece]] (1842), the [[Old Royal Palace]] (now the Greek Parliament Building, 1843), and the [[Old Parliament House, Athens|Old Parliament Building]] (1858). Schools and hospitals were established all over the (still small) Greek dominion. Due to the negative feelings of the Greek people toward non-Greek rule, historical attention to this aspect of his reign has been neglected.\n\nDuring 1836\u201337, Otto visited Germany, marrying a beautiful and talented 17-year-old, [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Duchess Amalia (Amelie) of Oldenburg]] (21 December 1818 to 20 May 1875). The wedding took place not in Greece but in [[Oldenburg]], on 22 November 1836; the marriage did not produce an heir, and the new queen made herself unpopular by interfering in the government and maintaining her [[Lutheran]] faith. Otto was unfaithful to his wife, and had an affair with [[Jane Digby]], a notorious woman his father had previously taken as a lover.<ref>Lovell, Mary S., ''A Scandalous Life: The Biography of Jane Digby'' (Fourth Estate, 1996) {{ISBN|978-1-85702-469-2}}</ref> {{Better source|date=August 2019}}\n\nDue to his having overtly undermined the king, Armansperg was dismissed from his duties by King Otto immediately upon his return from Germany. However, despite high hopes on the part of the Greeks, the Bavarian [[Ignaz von Rudhart|Rudhart]] was appointed chief minister, and the granting of a [[constitution]] was again postponed. The attempts of Otto to conciliate Greek sentiment through efforts to enlarge the frontiers of his kingdom, for example by the suggested acquisition of [[Crete]] in 1841, failed in their objective and only succeeded in embroiling him in conflict with the Great Powers.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n==Parties, finances and the church==\n{{Main|Early Greek Parties}}\n[[File:Grece armoiries(Otto).png|thumb|left|180px|Personal coat of arms of Otto]]\n\nThroughout his reign, King Otto found himself confronted by a recurring series of problems: partisanship of the Greeks, financial uncertainty, and ecclesiastical disputes.\n\nGreek parties in the Othonian era were based on two factors: the political activities of the diplomatic representatives of the [[Great Powers]] Russia, United Kingdom and France and the affiliation of Greek political figures with these diplomats.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n[[File:King Otto of Greece.jpg|thumb|A romantic portrayal of Otto in [[Evzones|Evzonas]] uniform, in front of ancient Greek ruins, by [[Gottlieb Bodmer]]]]\n\nAccording to [[Richard Clogg]], the financial uncertainty of the Othonian monarchy was the result of\n*1) Greece's poverty,\n*2) the concentration of land in the hands of a small number of wealthy \"primates\" like the [[Petros Mavromichalis|Mavromichalis]] family of [[Mani Peninsula|Mani]],\n\nand\n*3) the promise of 60,000,000 francs in loans from the Great Powers, which kept these nations involved in Greek internal affairs and the Crown constantly seeking to please one or the other power to ensure the flow of funds.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe political machinations of the Great Powers were personified in their three legates in Athens: the French [[Theobald Piscatory]], the Russian [[Gabriel Catacazy]], and the English [[Edmund Lyons, 1st Baron Lyons|Edmund Lyons]]. They informed their home governments on the activities of the Greeks, while serving as advisers to their respective allied parties within Greece.\n\nOtto pursued policies such as balancing power among all the parties and sharing offices among the parties, ostensibly to reduce the power of the parties while trying to bring a pro-Othon party into being. The parties, however, became the entree into government power and financial stability.\n\nThe effect of his (and his advisors') policies was to make the Great Powers' parties more powerful, not less. The Great Powers did not support curtailing Otto's increasing absolutism, however, which resulted in a near permanent conflict between Otto's absolute monarchy and the power bases of his Greek subjects.<ref name=\"Petropulos, John A. 1968\"/>\n\nOtto found himself confronted by a number of intractable [[ecclesiastical]] issues: 1) [[monasticism]], 2) [[Autocephaly]], 3) the king as head of the Church and 4) toleration of other churches. {{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nHis regents, Armansperg and Rundhart, established a controversial policy of [[Secularization|suppressing the monasteries]]. This was very upsetting to the Church hierarchy. Russia considered itself a stalwart defender of [[Eastern Orthodox|Orthodoxy]], but Orthodox believers were found in all three parties. Once he rid himself of his Bavarian advisers, Otto allowed the statutory dissolution of the monasteries to lapse.\n\nBy tradition dated back to the Byzantine era, the king was regarded by the Church as part of its head. {{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} On the issue of the Church's [[Autocephaly]] and his role as king within the Church, Otto was overwhelmed by the arcana of Orthodox Church doctrine and popular discontent with his Roman Catholicism<ref name=\"Petropulos, John A. 1968\"/> (while the Queen was Protestant).\n\nIn 1833, the regents had unilaterally declared the Autocephaly of the [[Church of Greece]].\nThis was a recognition of the ''de facto'' political situation, as the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|Patriarch of Constantinople]] was partially under the political control of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. However, faithful people, concerned that having a Catholic as the head of the Church of Greece would weaken the Orthodox Church, criticised the unilateral declaration of Autocephaly as [[Canon law|non-canonical]]. For the same reason, they likewise resisted the foreign, mostly [[Protestant]] missionaries who established schools throughout Greece.\n\n[[File:Otto and Amalia of Greece on a ride through Athens.jpg|thumb|240px|Otto with [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Amalia]] on a ride through Athens]]\n\nTolerance of other religions was over-supported by some in the English Party and others educated in the West as a symbol of Greece's progress as a [[Liberalism|liberal]] European state. In the end, power over the Church and education was ceded to the Russian Party, while the king maintained a veto over the decision of the [[Synod]] of Bishops. This was to keep balance and avoid discrediting Greece in the eyes of Western Europe as a backward, religiously intolerant society.<ref name=\"Petropulos, John A. 1968\"/>\n\nGreek society was in reality very tolerant of other religions. {{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} But after 400 years of religious oppression by the Ottomans, Greeks were very suspicious of imposed \"Liberal European progress\". Such forced \"progress\" was viewed as one more attempt against their faith and against their own understanding of freedom, as the main motto of the Greek Revolution was ''\"for the holy faith of Christ and the freedom of the homeland\"''; home and faith were inseparable, given also that the Church was the main contributor to the survival of the Greek language and Greek consciousness during Turkish occupation.\n\nCatholic communities had been established in Greece since the 13th century (Athens, Cyclades, Chios, Crete). Jewish communities also existed in the country, those arriving after the [[Expulsion of the Jews from Spain]] (1492) joining the earlier [[Romaniotes]], Jews who had been living there since the times of [[Apostle Paul]].<ref>Bowman, \"The Jews of Greece\", [http://www.umass.edu/judaic/anniversaryvolume/articles/30-F3-Bowman.pdf 421\u2013422] (PDF)</ref> Muslim families were still living in Greece during Otto's reign, since hostility was mainly against the Ottoman state and its depressive mechanisms and not against Muslim people.\n\n==3 September 1843 Revolution==\n{{main|3 September 1843 Revolution}}\n[[File:3\u03b7 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5.jpg|thumb|right|A painting representing the 3 September 1843 Revolution]]\n\nAlthough King Otto tried to function as an absolute monarch, as [[Thomas Gallant (historian)|Thomas Gallant]] writes, he \"was neither ruthless enough to be feared, nor compassionate enough to be loved, nor competent enough to be respected.\"<ref>[[Thomas W. Gallant|Gallant, Thomas W.]], ''Modern Greece'' (Oxford University Press, 2003) {{ISBN|0-340-76336-1}}</ref>\n\nBy 1843, public dissatisfaction with him had reached crisis proportions and there were demands for a Constitution. Initially Otto refused to grant a Constitution, but as soon as Bavarian troops were withdrawn from the kingdom, a [[3 September 1843 Revolution|popular revolt]] was launched.\n\nOn 3 September 1843, the infantry led by Colonel [[Dimitri Kalergis|Dimitris Kallergis]] and the respected Revolutionary captain and former President of the Athens City Council [[Ioannis Makriyannis|General Yiannis Makriyiannis]] assembled in [[Syntagma Square|Palace Square]] in front of the Palace in Athens.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Eventually joined by much of the population of the small capital, the crowd refused to disperse until the king agreed to grant a constitution, which would require that there be Greeks in the Council, that he convene a permanent National Assembly and that Otto personally thank the leaders of the uprising.\n\nLeft with little recourse now that his German troops were gone, King Otto gave in to the pressure and agreed to the demands of the crowd over the objections of his opinionated [[Queen Amalia of Greece|queen]]. This square was renamed [[Syntagma Square|Constitution Square]] (\u03a0\u03bb\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2) to commemorate (through to the present) the events of September 1843 \u2014 and to feature many later tumultuous events of Greek history.<ref>Tompkinson, John L., ''Athens: The City'' (Anagnosis Books, 1996) {{ISBN|960-87186-0-0}}</ref> Now for the first time, the king had Greeks in his Council and the French Party, the English Party and the Russian Party (according to which of the Great Powers' culture they most esteemed) vied for rank and power.\n\nThe king's prestige, which was based in large part on his support by the combined Great Powers, but mostly the support of the British, suffered in the ''[[Pacifico incident]]'' of 1850, when British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Henry Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston|Palmerston]] sent the British fleet to blockade the port of [[Piraeus]] with warships to exact reparation for injustice done to a British subject.<ref>Pacifico was a Jew of Portuguese nationality, merchant and the Portuguese Consul in Athens, who accidentally was also a British citizen because he was born in Gibraltar. After a robbery in his shop he asked for compensation from the Greek state, but nobody paid attention to him, not even the Portuguese government. Finally, he asked for help from the British ambassador, and his case was turned into the blockade of the port of Piraeus by the British Fleet.</ref>\n\n==Crimean War==\n{{See also|Epirus revolt of 1854}}\nThe ''[[Megali Idea|Great Idea]]'' (\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7 \u0399\u03b4\u03ad\u03b1), the dream of uniting all Greek populations of the Ottoman Empire, thereby restoring the [[Byzantine Empire]] under Christian rule, led him to contemplate entering the [[Crimean War]] on the side of Russia against Turkey and its British and French allies in 1853; the enterprise was unsuccessful and resulted in renewed intervention by the two Great Powers and a second blockade of the [[Piraeus]] port, forcing Greece to neutrality.\n\nThe continued inability of the royal couple to have children also raised the thorny issue of succession: the 1844 constitution insisted that Otto's successor had to be Orthodox, but as the king was childless, the only possible heirs were his younger brothers, [[Luitpold, Prince Regent of Bavaria|Luitpold]] and [[Prince Adalbert of Bavaria (1828\u20131875)|Adalbert]]. The staunch Catholicism of the Wittelsbachs complicated matters, as Luitpold refused to convert and Adalbert married [[Infanta Amalia of Spain]]. The sons of Adalbert, and especially the eldest, [[Prince Ludwig Ferdinand of Bavaria|Ludwig Ferdinand]], were now considered the most likely candidates, but due to the issue of religion, no definite arrangements were ever made.{{sfn|Jelavich|1961|pp=126\u2013127}}\n\nIn 1861, a student named [[Aristeidis Dosios]] (son of politician [[Konstantinos Dosios]]) attempted to murder [[Queen Amalia of Greece|Queen Amalia]] and was openly hailed as a hero. His attempt, however, also prompted spontaneous feelings of monarchism and sympathy towards the royal couple among the Greek population.<ref name=\"Brekis\">{{cite book |last=Brekis |first=Spyros |title=\u038a\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2 |trans-title=History of Modern Greece |language=Greek |year=2003 |isbn= }}</ref> {{Better source|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Exile and death ==\n{{main|23 October 1862 Revolution}}\n[[File:The expulsion of King Otto.jpg|thumb|left|The expulsion of Otto in 1862 as portrayed in a popular colour [[lithograph]]]]\n\nWhile Otto was visiting the [[Peloponnese]] in 1862 a new coup was launched and this time a [[Provisional Government]] was set up and summoned a National Convention. Ambassadors of the [[Great Powers]] urged King Otto not to resist, and the king and queen took refuge on a British warship and returned to [[Bavaria]] aboard (the same way they had come to Greece), taking with them the Greek royal regalia which they had brought from Bavaria in 1832. In 1863 the Greek National Assembly elected Prince William of Denmark, aged only 17, ''King of the Hellenes'' under the [[regnal name]] of [[George I of Greece|George I.]] \n\n[[File:OtonIdeGrecia1865.jpg|thumb|200px|Otto in [[Bavaria]], 1865]]\nIt has been suggested that had Otto and Amalia borne an heir, the king would not have been overthrown, as succession was also a major unresolved question at the time.<ref>[[John Van der Kiste]], ''Kings of the Hellenes'' (Sutton Publishing, 1994) {{ISBN|0-7509-2147-1}}</ref> However, the Constitution of 1843 made provision for his succession by his two younger brothers and their descendants.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nOtto died in the palace of the former bishops of [[Bamberg]], Germany, and was buried in the [[Theatinerkirche (M\u00fcnchen)|Theatiner Church]] in [[Munich]]. During his retirement, he would still wear the Greek traditional uniform, nowadays worn only by the [[evzones]] (Presidential Guards).\n\n\u0391ccording to witnesses{{who|date=August 2019}}, Otto's last words were \"Greece, my Greece, my beloved Greece\".<ref>Gallant 2015: 142-3;  2016: 73</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHe received the following honours:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Bavaria}}: Knight of the [[Order of St. Hubert]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Hof- und Staatshandbuch des K\u00f6nigreichs Bayern: 1833|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Qs9GAAAAcAAJ|year=1833|publisher=Landesamt|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Qs9GAAAAcAAJ/page/n133 7]}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of France (1794\u20131815, 1830\u20131958).svg}} [[July Monarchy|Kingdom of France]]: Grand Cross of the [[Legion of Honour]], ''July 1834''<ref>{{cite book| author = M. & B. Wattel | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = Les Grand'Croix de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur de 1805 \u00e0 nos jours. Titulaires fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =   |location= Paris |date = 2009 |publisher= Archives & Culture |at=  |volume=  | pages = | page = 420 | series =  | isbn = 978-2-35077-135-9| ref = M. et B. Wattel}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Spain (1785\u20131873, 1875\u20131931).svg}} [[History of Spain (1810\u201373)|Spain]]: Knight of the [[Order of the Golden Fleece#Spanish_Order|Order of the Golden Fleece]], ''13 June 1835''<ref>{{cite book|title=Gu\u00eda de forasteros en Madrid para el a\u00f1o de 1844|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d10NN6zDFBQC&pg=PA74|year=1844|publisher=En la Imprenta Nacional|page=74}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Russian Empire}}: Knight of the [[Order of St. Andrew]], ''June 1835''<ref>{{cite book|author=Sergey Semenovich Levin|title=Order of the Holy Apostle Andrew the First-called (1699-1917). Order of the Holy Great Martyr Catherine (1714-1917)|year=2003|chapter=Lists of Knights and Ladies|publication-place=Moscow|page=}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Swedish and Norwegian merchant flag 1818-1844.svg}} [[Sweden-Norway]]: Knight of the [[Royal Order of the Seraphim]], ''11 July 1835''<ref>{{cite book|title=Sveriges och Norges statskalender|year=1866|page=433|url=http://runeberg.org/sonkal/1866/0469.html|via=runeberg.org|accessd